@startuml

title CRM runtime (Phase 2) -- concurrent spot updates vs batch rate reads

participant "Feed thread" as Feed
participant "rate_engine" as Engine
participant "immer::atom<rate_snapshot>" as Atom
participant "Consumer thread(s)" as Consumer

== Spot update (single producer) ==

Feed -> Engine : update(driver_quote)
activate Engine
Engine -> Engine : locate driver edge in fixed topology\n(O(1), topology never changes)
Engine -> Engine : walk the subtree hanging off that edge\nrecompute log_rate + as_of per descendant vertex
Engine -> Atom : update(fn: old_snapshot -> new_snapshot)\n(persistent vector -- only touched\nentries are copied, rest shared)
note right of Atom
  Wait-free publish. Old snapshot stays
  valid for any reader still holding it --
  no reader ever blocks a writer or vice versa.
end note
deactivate Engine

== Batch read (many concurrent consumers) ==

Consumer -> Engine : rates(pairs[1..N])
activate Engine
Engine -> Atom : load() -- ONE atomic read for the whole batch
Atom --> Engine : snapshot (immutable, private view)
loop for each requested pair
    Engine -> Engine : rate = exp(log_rate[quote] - log_rate[base])
    Engine -> Engine : staleness = now - min(as_of[base], as_of[quote])
    Engine -> Engine : status = staleness_policy.evaluate(staleness)
end
Engine --> Consumer : vector<derived_rate>
deactivate Engine

note over Feed, Consumer
  No locks anywhere on this path. Producer and any number of
  consumers proceed independently; a consumer mid-batch never
  sees a torn mix of old/new rates because it holds one snapshot
  for the entire batch.
end note

@enduml
